\chapter{sTROFFet:  Troff code in EZ

}\leftindent{
}\leftindent{If the options available from menucards, \italic{lookz}, 
\italic{header}/footer, and \italic{compchar} don't meet your formatting 
needs, you may want to use commands from \italic{troff}, the UNIX "typeset 
runoff" formatting package, in a \italic{troff} inset.


A troff inset allows you to include a piece of raw troff code in your EZ 
documents. Troff commands that appear in a troff inset do not get formatted 
during EZ's printing and/or previewing operations, and are instead passed on 
to the underlying formatter, the troff program itself.  This provides an 
alternative to the use of the \bold{FormatNote} style available from the 
\italic{Region }menucard, which has been the cause of many problems for novice 
users.  They all too often unknowingly include large sections of text into a 
formatnote, which leads to unexpected printed results.


These are troff insets, the way they are most commonly used:


